description: From Latin incūsus, past participle of incūdō, from in- + cūdō.

entries.meaning: hammered or pressed in (usually on a coin)
examples: The back of the coin bears an incuse coat of arms.

entries.meaning: an impression hammered or pressed (onto a coin)
examples: This coin's incuse is of a most curious design.

verbs.description: incuse (third-person singular simple present incuses, present participle incusing, simple past and past participle incused)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To hammer or press (usually onto a coin)
examples: There is a long tradition of monarchs having their own figure incused in their kingdom's coins.
